msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/crates-io-disallows-wildcard-dependencies.md:1
msgid "Crates.io disallows wildcard dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/crates-io-disallows-wildcard-dependencies.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.6](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.6-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/crates-io-disallows-wildcard-dependencies.md:5
msgid ""
"Crates.io will not allow you to upload a package with a wildcard dependency. "
"In other words, these:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/crates-io-disallows-wildcard-dependencies.md:8
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[dependencies]\n"
"regex = \"*\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/crates-io-disallows-wildcard-dependencies.md:13
msgid ""
"A wildcard dependency means that you work with any possible version of your "
"dependency. This is highly unlikely to be true, and would cause unnecessary "
"breakage in the ecosystem."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/crates-io-disallows-wildcard-dependencies.md:17
msgid ""
"Instead, depend on a version range. For example, `^` is the default, so you "
"could use"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/crates-io-disallows-wildcard-dependencies.md:20
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[dependencies]\n"
"regex = \"1.0.0\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/crates-io-disallows-wildcard-dependencies.md:25
msgid "instead. `>`, `<=`, and all of the other, non-`*` ranges work as well."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/multi-file-examples.md:1
msgid "Multi-file examples"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/multi-file-examples.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.22](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.22-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/multi-file-examples.md:5
msgid ""
"Cargo has an `examples` feature for showing people how to use your package. "
"By putting individual files inside of the top-level `examples` directory, "
"you can create multiple examples."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/multi-file-examples.md:9
msgid ""
"But what if your example is too big for a single file? Cargo supports adding "
"sub-directories inside of `examples`, and looks for a `main.rs` inside of "
"them to build the example. It looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/multi-file-examples.md:13
msgid ""
"```text\n"
"my-package\n"
" └──src\n"
"     └── lib.rs // code here\n"
" └──examples \n"
"     └── simple-example.rs // a single-file example\n"
"     └── complex-example\n"
"        └── helper.rs\n"
"        └── main.rs // a more complex example that also uses `helper` as a "
"submodule\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/replacing-dependencies-with-patch.md:1
msgid "Replacing dependencies with patch"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/replacing-dependencies-with-patch.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.21](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.21-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/replacing-dependencies-with-patch.md:5
msgid ""
"The `[patch]` section of your `Cargo.toml` can be used when you want to "
"override certain parts of your dependency graph."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/replacing-dependencies-with-patch.md:8
msgid ""
"Cargo has a `[replace]` feature that is similar; while we don't intend to "
"deprecate or remove `[replace]`, you should prefer `[patch]` in all "
"circumstances."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/replacing-dependencies-with-patch.md:11
msgid ""
"So what’s it look like? Let’s say we have a Cargo.toml that looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/replacing-dependencies-with-patch.md:13
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[dependencies]\n"
"foo = \"1.2.3\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/replacing-dependencies-with-patch.md:18
msgid ""
"In addition, our `foo` package depends on a `bar` crate, and we find a bug "
"in `bar`. To test this out, we’d download the source code for `bar`, and "
"then update our `Cargo.toml`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/cargo-and-crates-io/replacing-dependencies-with-patch.md:22
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[dependencies]\n"
