#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:1
msgid "`..=` for inclusive ranges"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:5
msgid ""
"Since well before Rust 1.0, you’ve been able to create exclusive ranges "
"with .. like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:8
msgid ""
"```\n"
"for i in 1..3 {\n"
"    println!(\"i: {}\", i);\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:14
msgid ""
"This will print `i: 1` and then `i: 2`. Today, you can now create an "
"inclusive range, like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:19
#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:35
#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:66
msgid "\"i: {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:23
msgid ""
"This will print `i: 1` and then `i: 2` like before, but also `i: 3`; the "
"three is included in the range. Inclusive ranges are especially useful if "
"you want to iterate over every possible value in a range. For example, this "
"is a surprising Rust program:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:30
#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:61
msgid "// ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:41
msgid ""
"What does this program do? The answer: nothing. The warning we get when "
"compiling has a hint:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:54
msgid ""
"That’s right, since `i` is a `u8`, this overflows, and is the same as "
"writing `for i in 0..0`, so the loop executes zero times."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:57
msgid "We can do this with inclusive ranges, however:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/inclusive-ranges.md:72
msgid ""
"This will produce those 256 lines of output you might have been expecting."
