#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/index.md:1
msgid "Error handling and Panics"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/index.md:5
msgid ""
"In this chapter of the guide, we discuss a few improvements to error "
"handling in Rust. The most notable of these is [the introduction of the `?` "
"operator](rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-"
"easier-error-handling.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/aborting-on-panic.md:1
msgid "Aborting on panic"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/aborting-on-panic.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.10](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.10-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/aborting-on-panic.md:5
msgid ""
"By default, Rust programs will unwind the stack when a `panic!` happens. If "
"you'd prefer an immediate abort instead, you can configure this in `Cargo."
"toml`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/aborting-on-panic.md:8
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[profile.debug]\n"
"panic = \"abort\"\n"
"\n"
"[profile.release]\n"
"panic = \"abort\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/aborting-on-panic.md:16
msgid ""
"Why might you choose to do this? By removing support for unwinding, you'll "
"get smaller binaries. You will lose the ability to catch panics. Which "
"choice is right for you depends on exactly what you're doing."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:1
msgid "Controlling panics with `std::panic`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.9](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.9-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:5
msgid ""
"There is a `std::panic` module, which includes methods for halting the "
"unwinding process started by a panic:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:12
msgid "\"hello!\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:17
msgid "\"oh no!\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:22
msgid ""
"In general, Rust distinguishes between two ways that an operation can fail:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:24
msgid "Due to an _expected problem_, like a file not being found."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:25
msgid ""
"Due to an _unexpected problem_, like an index being out of bounds for an "
"array."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:27
msgid ""
"Expected problems usually arise from conditions that are outside of your "
"control; robust code should be prepared for anything its environment might "
"throw at it. In Rust, expected problems are handled via [the `Result` type]"
"(http://doc.rust-lang.org/std/result/index.html), which allows a function to "
"return information about the problem to its caller, which can then handle "
"the error in a fine-grained way."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:35
msgid ""
"Unexpected problems are _bugs_: they arise due to a contract or assertion "
"being violated. Since they are unexpected, it doesn't make sense to handle "
"them in a fine-grained way. Instead, Rust employs a \"fail fast\" approach "
"by _panicking_, which by default unwinds the stack (running destructors but "
"no other code) of the thread which discovered the error. Other threads "
"continue running, but will discover the panic any time they try to "
"communicate with the panicked thread (whether through channels or shared "
"memory). Panics thus abort execution up to some \"isolation boundary\", with "
"code on the other side of the boundary still able to run, and perhaps to "
"\"recover\" from the panic in some very coarse-grained way. A server, for "
"example, does not necessarily need to go down just because of an assertion "
"failure in one of its threads."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:47
msgid ""
"It's also worth noting that programs may choose to _abort_ instead of "
"unwind, and so catching panics may not work. If your code relies on "
"`catch_unwind`, you should add this to your Cargo.toml:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:51
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[profile.debug]\n"
"panic = \"unwind\"\n"
"\n"
"[profile.release]\n"
"panic = \"unwind\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:59
msgid ""
"If any of your users choose to abort, they'll get a compile-time failure."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:61
msgid ""
"The `catch_unwind` API offers a way to introduce new isolation boundaries "
"_within a thread_. There are a couple of key motivating examples:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:64
msgid "Embedding Rust in other languages"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:65
msgid "Abstractions that manage threads"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:66
msgid ""
"Test frameworks, because tests may panic and you don't want that to kill the "
"test runner"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:68
msgid ""
"For the first case, unwinding across a language boundary is undefined "
"behavior, and often leads to segfaults in practice. Allowing panics to be "
"caught means that you can safely expose Rust code via a C API, and translate "
"unwinding into an error on the C side."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:73
msgid ""
"For the second case, consider a threadpool library. If a thread in the pool "
"panics, you generally don't want to kill the thread itself, but rather catch "
"the panic and communicate it to the client of the pool. The `catch_unwind` "
"API is paired with `resume_unwind`, which can then be used to restart the "
"panicking process on the client of the pool, where it belongs."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:79
msgid ""
"In both cases, you're introducing a new isolation boundary within a thread, "
"and then translating the panic into some other form of error elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:1
msgid "`?` in `main` and tests"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:5
msgid ""
"Rust's error handling revolves around returning `Result<T, E>` and using `?` "
"to propagate errors. For those who write many small programs and, hopefully, "
"many tests, one common paper cut has been mixing entry points such as `main` "
"and `#[test]`s with error handling."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:10
msgid "As an example, you might have tried to write:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:16
#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:29
#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:70
msgid "\"bar.txt\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:20
msgid ""
"Since `?` works by propagating the `Result` with an early return to the "
"enclosing function, the snippet above does not work, and results today in "
"the following error:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:36
msgid ""
"To solve this problem in Rust 2015, you might have written something like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:39
msgid "// Rust 2015\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:45
msgid "// real logic..\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:51
msgid "\"Application error: {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:57
msgid ""
"However, in this case, the `run` function has all the interesting logic and "
"`main` is just boilerplate. The problem is even worse for `#[test]`s, since "
"there tend to be a lot more of them."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:61
msgid ""
"In Rust 2018 you can instead let your `#[test]`s and `main` functions return "
"a `Result`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:65
msgid "// Rust 2018\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:76
msgid ""
"In this case, if say the file doesn't exist and there is an `Err(err)` "
"somewhere, then `main` will exit with an error code (not `0`) and print out "
"a `Debug` representation of `err`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:80
msgid "More details"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:82
msgid ""
"Getting `-> Result<..>` to work in the context of `main` and `#[test]`s is "
"not magic. It is all backed up by a `Termination` trait which all valid "
"return types of `main` and testing functions must implement. The trait is "
"defined as:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:92
msgid ""
"When setting up the entry point for your application, the compiler will use "
"this trait and call `.report()` on the `Result` of the `main` function you "
"have written."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:95
msgid ""
"Two simplified example implementations of this trait for `Result` and `()` "
"are:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:116
msgid "\"Error: {:?}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:125
msgid ""
"As you can see in the case of `()`, a success code is simply returned. In "
"the case of `Result`, the success case delegates to the implementation for "
"`()` but prints out an error message and a failure exit code on `Err(..)`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:129
msgid ""
"To learn more about the finer details, consult either [the tracking issue]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/43301) or [the RFC](https://github."
"com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/1937-ques-in-main.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:1
msgid "The `?` operator for easier error handling"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.13](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.13-brightgreen.svg) for `Result<T, E>`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:5
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.22](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.22-brightgreen.svg) for `Option<T>`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:7
msgid ""
"Rust has gained a new operator, `?`, that makes error handling more pleasant "
"by reducing the visual noise involved. It does this by solving one simple "
"problem. To illustrate, imagine we had some code to read some data from a "
"file:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:15
#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:49
#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:73
msgid "\"username.txt\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:31
msgid ""
"Note: this code could be made simpler with a single call to [`std::fs::"
"read_to_string`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/std/fs/fn.read_to_string."
"html), but we're writing it all out manually here to have an example with "
"multiple errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:36
msgid ""
"This code has two paths that can fail, opening the file and reading the data "
"from it. If either of these fail to work, we'd like to return an error from "
"`read_username_from_file`. Doing so involves `match`ing on the result of the "
"I/O operations. In simple cases like this though, where we are only "
"propagating errors up the call stack, the matching is just boilerplate - "
"seeing it written out, in the same pattern every time, doesn't provide the "
"reader with a great deal of useful information."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:44
msgid "With `?`, the above code looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:58
msgid ""
"The `?` is shorthand for the entire match statements we wrote earlier. In "
"other words, `?` applies to a `Result` value, and if it was an `Ok`, it "
"unwraps it and gives the inner value. If it was an `Err`, it returns from "
"the function you're currently in. Visually, it is much more straightforward. "
"Instead of an entire match statement, now we are just using the single \"?\" "
"character to indicate that here we are handling errors in the standard way, "
"by passing them up the call stack."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:66
msgid ""
"Seasoned Rustaceans may recognize that this is the same as the `try!` macro "
"that's been available since Rust `1.0`. And indeed, they are the same. "
"Previously, `read_username_from_file` could have been implemented like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:82
msgid ""
"So why extend the language when we already have a macro? There are multiple "
"reasons. First, `try!` has proved to be extremely useful, and is used often "
"in idiomatic Rust. It is used so often that we think it's worth having a "
"sweet syntax. This sort of evolution is one of the great advantages of a "
"powerful macro system: speculative extensions to the language syntax can be "
"prototyped and iterated on without modifying the language itself, and in "
"return, macros that turn out to be especially useful can indicate missing "
"language features. This evolution, from `try!` to `?` is a great example."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:91
msgid ""
"One of the reasons `try!` needs a sweeter syntax is that it is quite "
"unattractive when multiple invocations of `try!` are used in succession. "
"Consider:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:99
msgid "as opposed to"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:105
msgid ""
"The first is quite difficult to scan visually, and each layer of error "
"handling prefixes the expression with an additional call to `try!`. This "
"brings undue attention to the trivial error propagation, obscuring the main "
"code path, in this example the calls to `foo`, `bar` and `baz`. This sort of "
"method chaining with error handling occurs in situations like the builder "
"pattern."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:112
msgid ""
"Finally, the dedicated syntax will make it easier in the future to produce "
"nicer error messages tailored specifically to `?`, whereas it is difficult "
"to produce nice errors for macro-expanded code generally."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:116
msgid ""
"You can use `?` with `Result<T, E>`s, but also with `Option<T>`. In that "
"case, `?` will return a value for `Some(T)` and return `None` for `None`. "
"One current restriction is that you cannot use `?` for both in the same "
"function, as the return type needs to match the type you use `?` on. In the "
"future, this restriction will be lifted."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/index.md:1
msgid "Macros"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/index.md:5
msgid ""
"In this chapter of the guide, we discuss a few improvements to the macro "
"system. A notable addition here is the introduction of [custom derive macros]"
"(rust-2018/macros/custom-derive.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/at-most-once.md:1
msgid "At most one repetition"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/at-most-once.md:3
msgid ""
"In Rust 2018, we have made a couple of changes to the macros-by-example "
"syntax."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/at-most-once.md:5
msgid ""
"We have added a new Kleene operator `?` which means \"at most one\" "
"repetition. This operator does not accept a separator token."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/at-most-once.md:7
msgid ""
"We have disallowed using `?` as a separator to remove ambiguity with `?`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/at-most-once.md:9
msgid "For example, consider the following Rust 2015 code:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/at-most-once.md:11
msgid ""
"```rust2018\n"
"macro_rules! foo {\n"
"    ($a:ident, $b:expr) => {\n"
"        println!(\"{}\", $a);\n"
"        println!(\"{}\", $b);\n"
"    }\n"
"    ($a:ident) => {\n"
"        println!(\"{}\", $a);\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/at-most-once.md:23
msgid ""
"Macro `foo` can be called with 1 or 2 arguments; the second one is optional, "
"but you need a whole other matcher to represent this possibility. This is "
"annoying if your matchers are long. In Rust 2018, one can simply write the "
"following:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/at-most-once.md:28
msgid ""
"```rust2018\n"
"macro_rules! foo {\n"
"    ($a:ident $(, $b:expr)?) => {\n"
"        println!(\"{}\", $a);\n"
"\n"
"        $(\n"
"            println!(\"{}\", $b);\n"
"         )?\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/custom-derive.md:1
msgid "Custom Derive"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/custom-derive.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.15](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.15-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/custom-derive.md:5
msgid ""
"In Rust, you’ve always been able to automatically implement some traits "
"through the derive attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/custom-derive.md:15
msgid ""
"The `Debug` trait is then implemented for `Pet`, with vastly less "
"boilerplate. For example, without `derive`, you'd have to write this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/custom-derive.md:29
msgid "\"Pet\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/custom-derive.md:31
msgid "\"name\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/custom-derive.md:42
msgid ""
"However, this only worked for traits provided as part of the standard "
"library; it was not customizable. But now, you can tell Rust what to do when "
"someone wants to derive your trait. This is used heavily in popular crates "
"like [serde](https://serde.rs/) and [Diesel](http://diesel.rs/)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/custom-derive.md:47
msgid ""
"For more, including learning how to build your own custom derive, see [The "
