#: src/rust-2018/module-system/more-visibility-modifiers.md:1
msgid "More visibility modifiers"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/more-visibility-modifiers.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.18](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.18-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/more-visibility-modifiers.md:5
msgid ""
"You can use the `pub` keyword to make something a part of a module's public "
"interface. But in addition, there are some new forms:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/more-visibility-modifiers.md:14
msgid ""
"The first form makes the `Foo` struct public to your entire crate, but not "
"externally. The second form is similar, but makes `Bar` public for one other "
"module, `a::b::c` in this case."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/nested-imports-with-use.md:1
msgid "Nested imports with `use`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/nested-imports-with-use.md:5
msgid ""
"A new way to write `use` statements has been added to Rust: nested import "
"groups. If you’ve ever written a set of imports like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/nested-imports-with-use.md:14
msgid "You can now write this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/nested-imports-with-use.md:17
msgid "// on one line\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/nested-imports-with-use.md:22
msgid "// with some more breathing room\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/nested-imports-with-use.md:35
msgid "This can reduce some repetition, and make things a bit more clear."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:1
msgid "Path clarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: beta](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-beta-orange.svg) ![Minimum Rust version: nightly]"
"(https://img.shields.io/badge/Minimum%20Rust%20Version-nightly-red.svg) for "
"\"uniform paths\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:6
msgid ""
"The module system is often one of the hardest things for people new to Rust. "
"Everyone has their own things that take time to master, of course, but "
"there's a root cause for why it's so confusing to many: while there are "
"simple and consistent rules defining the module system, their consequences "
"can feel inconsistent, counterintuitive and mysterious."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:12
msgid ""
"As such, the 2018 edition of Rust introduces a few new module system "
"features, but they end up _simplifying_ the module system, to make it more "
"clear as to what is going on."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:16
msgid "Here's a brief summary:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:18
msgid "`extern crate` is no longer needed in 99% of circumstances."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:19
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:116
msgid "The `crate` keyword refers to the current crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:20
msgid ""
"Absolute paths begin with a crate name, where the keyword `crate` refers to "
"the current crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:22
msgid ""
"A `foo.rs` and `foo/` subdirectory may coexist; `mod.rs` is no longer needed "
"when placing submodules in a subdirectory."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:25
msgid ""
"These may seem like arbitrary new rules when put this way, but the mental "
"model is now significantly simplified overall. Read on for more details!"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:28
msgid ""
"Additionally, in nightly, there's an additional possible tweak to paths "
"called \"Uniform paths\". This is backwards compatible with the new path "
"changes. Uniform paths have a dedicated section at the end of this guide."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:34
msgid "Let's talk about each new feature in turn."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:36
msgid "No more `extern crate`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:38
msgid ""
"This one is quite straightforward: you no longer need to write `extern "
"crate` to import a crate into your project. Before:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:51
msgid "After:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:61
msgid ""
"Now, to add a new crate to your project, you can add it to your `Cargo."
"toml`, and then there is no step two. If you're not using Cargo, you already "
"had to pass `--extern` flags to give `rustc` the location of external "
"crates, so you'd just keep doing what you were doing there as well."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:66
msgid ""
"One small note here: `cargo fix` will not currently automate this change. We "
"may have it do this for you in the future."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:69
msgid "An exception"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:71
msgid ""
"There's one exception to this rule, and that's the \"sysroot\" crates. These "
"are the crates distributed with Rust itself. We'd eventually like to remove "
"the requirement for `extern crate` for them as well, but it hasn't shipped "
"yet."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:75
msgid "You'll need to use `extern crate` for:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:77
msgid "`proc_macro`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:79
msgid "Additionally, you would need to use it for:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:81
msgid "`core`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:82
msgid "`std`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:84
msgid ""
"However, `extern crate std;` is already implicit, and with `#![no_std]`, "
"`extern crate core;` is already implicit. You'll only need these in highly "
"specialized situations."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:88
msgid "Finally, on nightly, you'll need it for crates like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:90
msgid "`alloc`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:91
msgid "`test`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:95
msgid ""
"One other use for `extern crate` was to import macros; that's no longer "
"needed. Check [the macro section](rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.html) for "
"more."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:98
msgid "If you've been using `as` to rename your crate like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:106
msgid ""
"then removing the `extern crate` line on its own won't work. You'll need to "
"do this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:114
msgid "This change will need to happen in any module that uses `f`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:118
msgid ""
"In `use` declarations and in other code, you can refer to the root of the "
"current crate with the `crate::` prefix. For instance, `crate::foo::bar` "
"will always refer to the name `bar` inside the module `foo`, from anywhere "
"else in the same crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:123
msgid ""
"The prefix `::` previously referred to either the crate root or an external "
"crate; it now unambiguously refers to an external crate. For instance, `::"
"foo::bar` always refers to the name `bar` inside the external crate `foo`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:127
msgid "Changes to paths"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:129
msgid ""
"In Rust 2018, paths in `use` declarations _must_ begin with a crate name, "
"`crate`, `self`, or `super`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:132
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:287
msgid "Code that looked like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:148
msgid "Now looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:152
msgid "// 'futures' is the name of a crate\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:159
msgid "// 'crate' means the current crate\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:164
msgid ""
"In addition, all of these path forms are available outside of `use` "
"declarations as well, which eliminates many sources of confusion. Consider "
"this code in Rust 2015:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:174
msgid "// this works!\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:177
msgid "// so why doesn't this work?\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:182
msgid "// this works\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:188
msgid "// ... so why doesn't this work\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:194
msgid ""
"In real code, you couldn't repeat `mod submodule`, and `function` would be "
"defined in the first `mod` block."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:197
msgid ""
"In the `futures` example, the `my_poll` function signature is incorrect, "
"because `submodule` contains no items named `futures`; that is, this path is "
"considered relative. `use futures::` works even though a lone `futures::` "
"doesn't! With `std` it can be even more confusing, as you never wrote the "
"`extern crate std;` line at all. So why does it work in `main` but not in a "
"submodule? Same thing: it's a relative path because it's not in a `use` "
"declaration. `extern crate std;` is inserted at the crate root, so it's fine "
"in `main`, but it doesn't exist in the submodule at all."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:206
msgid "Let's look at how this change affects things:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:210
msgid "// no more `extern crate futures;`\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:214
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:217
msgid "// 'futures' is the name of a crate, so this works\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:223
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:229
msgid "// 'std' is the name of a crate, so this works\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:234
msgid "Much more straightforward."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:236
msgid "No more `mod.rs`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:238
msgid "In Rust 2015, if you have a submodule:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:241
msgid ""
"///  foo.rs \n"
"///  or \n"
"///  foo/mod.rs\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:248
msgid ""
"It can live in `foo.rs` or `foo/mod.rs`. If it has submodules of its own, it "
"_must_ be `foo/mod.rs`. So a `bar` submodule of `foo` would live at `foo/bar."
"rs`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:252
msgid "In Rust 2018, `mod.rs` is no longer needed."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:255
msgid ""
"///  foo.rs \n"
"///  foo/bar.rs\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:259
msgid "/// in foo.rs\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:264
msgid ""
"`foo.rs` can just be `foo.rs`, and the submodule is still `foo/bar.rs`. This "
"eliminates the special name, and if you have a bunch of files open in your "
"editor, you can clearly see their names, instead of having a bunch of tabs "
"named `mod.rs`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:269
msgid "Uniform paths"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:271
msgid "Uniform paths are a nightly-only feature."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:273
msgid ""
"The uniform paths variant of Rust 2018 simplifies and unifies path handling "
"compared to Rust 2015. In Rust 2015, paths work differently in `use` "
"declarations than they do elsewhere. In particular, paths in `use` "
"declarations would always start from the crate root, while paths in other "
"code implicitly started from the current module. Those differences didn't "
"have any effect in the top-level module, which meant that everything would "
"seem straightforward until working on a project large enough to have "
"submodules."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:281
msgid ""
"In the uniform paths variant of Rust 2018, paths in `use` declarations and "
"in other code always work the same way, both in the top-level module and in "
"any submodule. You can always use a relative path from the current module, a "
"path starting from an external crate name, or a path starting with `crate`, "
"`super`, or `self`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:319
msgid ""
"will look exactly the same in Rust 2018, except that you can delete the "
"`extern crate` line:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:323
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:354
msgid "// Rust 2018 (uniform paths variant)\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:350
msgid ""
"With Rust 2018, however, the same code will also work completely unmodified "
"in a submodule:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:383
msgid ""
"This makes it easy to move code around in a project, and avoids introducing "
"additional complexity to multi-module projects."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:386
msgid ""
"If a path is ambiguous, such as if you have an external crate and a local "
"module or item with the same name, you'll get an error, and you'll need to "
"either rename one of the conflicting names or explicitly disambiguate the "
"path. To explicitly disambiguate a path, use `::name` for an external crate "
"name, or `self::name` for a local module or item."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:1
msgid "Raw identifiers"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:5
msgid ""
"Rust, like many programming languages, has the concept of \"keywords\". "
"These identifiers mean something to the language, and so you cannot use them "
"in places like variable names, function names, and other places. Raw "
"identifiers let you use keywords where they would not normally be allowed."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:10
msgid "For example, `match` is a keyword. If you try to compile this function:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:18
msgid "You'll get this error:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:28
msgid "You can write this with a raw identifier:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:36
msgid "\"foo\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:36
msgid "\"foobar\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:40
msgid "Note the `r#` prefix on both the function name as well as the call."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:42
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:44
msgid ""
"This feature is useful for a few reasons, but the primary motivation was "
"inter-edition situations. For example, `try` is not a keyword in the 2015 "
"edition, but is in the 2018 edition. So if you have a library that is "
"written in Rust 2015 and has a `try` function, to call it in Rust 2018, "
"you'll need to use the raw identifier."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:50
msgid "New keywords"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:52
msgid "The new confirmed keywords in edition 2018 are:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:54
msgid "`async` and `await`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:58
msgid ""
"Here, `async` is reserved for use in `async fn` as well as in `async ||` "
"closures and `async { .. }` blocks. Meanwhile, `await` is reserved to keep "
"our options open with respect to `await!(expr)` syntax. See [RFC 2394]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/2394-async_await."
"md#final-syntax-for-the-await-expression) for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:62
msgid "`try`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:66
msgid ""
"The `do catch { .. }` blocks have been renamed to `try { .. }` and to "
"support that, the keyword `try` is reserved in edition 2018. See [RFC 2388]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/2388) for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/index.md:1
msgid "Ownership and lifetimes"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/index.md:5
msgid ""
"In this chapter of the guide, we discuss a few improvements to ownership and "
"lifetimes. One of the most notable of these is [default match binding modes]"
"(rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:1
msgid "Default match bindings"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:5
msgid ""
"Have you ever had a borrowed `Option<T>` and tried to match on it? You "
"probably wrote this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:9
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:23
msgid "\"hello\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:12
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:26
msgid "\"s is: {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:17
msgid ""
"In Rust 2015, this would fail to compile, and you would have to write the "
"following instead:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:31
msgid ""
"Rust 2018, by contrast, will infer the `&`s and `ref`s, and your original "
"code will Just Work."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:34
msgid ""
"This affects not just `match`, but patterns everywhere, such as in `let` "
"statements, closure arguments, and `for` loops."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:39
msgid ""
"The mental model of patterns has shifted a bit with this change, to bring it "
"into line with other aspects of the language. For example, when writing a "
"`for` loop, you can iterate over borrowed contents of a collection by "
"borrowing the collection itself:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:50
msgid ""
"The idea is that an `&T` can be understood as a _borrowed view of `T`_, and "
"so when you iterate, match, or otherwise destructure a `&T` you get a "
"borrowed view of its internals as well."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:54
msgid ""
"More formally, patterns have a \"binding mode,\" which is either by value "
"(`x`), by reference (`ref x`), or by mutable reference (`ref mut x`). In "
"Rust 2015, `match` always started in by-value mode, and required you to "
"explicitly write `ref` or `ref mut` in patterns to switch to a borrowing "
"mode. In Rust 2018, the type of the value being matched informs the binding "
"mode, so that if you match against an `&Option<String>` with a `Some` "
"variant, you are put into `ref` mode automatically, giving you a borrowed "
"view of the internal data. Similarly, `&mut Option<String>` would give you a "
"`ref mut` view."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/lifetime-elision-in-impl.md:1
msgid "Lifetime elision in impl"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/lifetime-elision-in-impl.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.31](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.31-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/lifetime-elision-in-impl.md:5
msgid ""
"When writing `impl` blocks, you can now elide lifetime annotations in some "
"situations."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/lifetime-elision-in-impl.md:8
msgid "Consider a trait like `MyIterator`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/lifetime-elision-in-impl.md:17
msgid ""
"In Rust 2015, if we wanted to implement this iterator for mutable references "
"to `Iterators`, we'd need to write this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/lifetime-elision-in-impl.md:29
msgid "Note all of the `'a` annotations. In Rust 2018, we can write this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/lifetime-elision-in-impl.md:40
msgid ""
"Similarly, lifetime annotations can appear due to a struct that contains "
"references:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/lifetime-elision-in-impl.md:50
msgid "In Rust 2015, to implement `Drop` on this struct, we'd write:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/lifetime-elision-in-impl.md:62
msgid ""
"But in Rust 2018, we can combine elision with [the anonymous lifetime]"
"(rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.html) and write "
"this instead."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:1
msgid "Non-lexical lifetimes"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:5
msgid ""
"The borrow checker has been enhanced to accept more code, via a mechanism "
"called \"non-lexical lifetimes.\" Consider this example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:18
msgid "In older Rust, this is a compile-time error:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:32
msgid ""
"This is because lifetimes follow \"lexical scope\"; that is, the borrow from "
"`y` is considered to be held until `y` goes out of scope at the end of "
"`main`, even though we never use `y` again. This code is fine, but the "
"borrow checker could not handle it."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:36
msgid "Today, this code will compile just fine."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:38
msgid "Better errors"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:40
msgid "What if we did use `y`, like this?"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:48
msgid "\"y: {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:52
msgid "Here's the error:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:67
msgid "With non-lexical lifetimes, the error changes slightly:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:69
msgid ""
"```text\n"
"error[E0502]: cannot borrow `x` as mutable because it is also borrowed as "
"immutable\n"
" --> src/main.rs:5:13\n"
"  |\n"
"4 |     let y = &x;\n"
"  |             -- immutable borrow occurs here\n"
"5 |     let z = &mut x;\n"
"  |             ^^^^^^ mutable borrow occurs here\n"
"6 |     \n"
"7 |     println!(\"y: {}\", y);\n"
"  |                       - borrow later used here\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/non-lexical-lifetimes.md:82
msgid ""
"Instead of pointing to where `y` goes out of scope, it shows you where the "
"conflicting borrow occurs. This makes these sorts of errors _far_ easier to "
"debug."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:1
msgid "Simpler lifetimes in `static` and `const`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:5
msgid ""
"In older Rust, you had to explicitly write the `'static` lifetime in any "
"`static` or `const` that needed a lifetime:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:10
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:13
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:22
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:25
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:34
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:39
msgid "\"Ferris\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:17
msgid ""
"But `'static` is the only possible lifetime there. So Rust now assumes the "
"`'static` lifetime, and you don't have to write it out:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:29
msgid "In some situations, this can remove a _lot_ of boilerplate:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:32
msgid "// old\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:34
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/simpler-lifetimes-in-static-and-const.md:39
msgid "\"Bors\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:1
msgid "`T: 'a` inference in structs"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:5
msgid ""
"An annotation in the form of `T: 'a`, where `T` is either a type or another "
"lifetime, is called an _\"outlives\"_ requirement. Note that _\"outlives\"_ "
"also implies `'a: 'a`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:9
msgid ""
"One way in which edition 2018 helps you out in maintaining flow when writing "
"programs is by removing the need to explicitly annotate these `T: 'a` "
"outlives requirements in `struct` definitions. Instead, the requirements "
"will be inferred from the fields present in the definitions."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:14
msgid "Consider the following `struct` definitions in Rust 2015:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:22
msgid "// or written with a `where` clause:\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:28
msgid "// with nested references:\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:34
msgid "// using an associated type:\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:45
msgid ""
"In Rust 2018, since the requirements are inferred, you can instead write:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:67
msgid ""
"If you prefer to be more explicit in some cases, that is still possible."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:71
msgid ""
"For more details, see [the tracking issue](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"issues/44493) and [the RFC](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/2093)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:1
msgid "`'_`, the anonymous lifetime"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:5
msgid ""
"Rust 2018 allows you to explicitly mark where a lifetime is elided, for "
"types where this elision might otherwise be unclear. To do this, you can use "
"the special lifetime `'_` much like you can explicitly mark that a type is "
"inferred with the syntax `let x: _ = ..;`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:10
msgid ""
"Let's say, for whatever reason, that we have a simple wrapper around `&'a "
"str`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:16
msgid "In Rust 2015, you might have written:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:36
msgid "In Rust 2018, you can instead write:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:59
msgid ""
"In the Rust 2015 snippet above, we've used `-> StrWrap`. However, unless you "
"take a look at the definition of `StrWrap`, it is not clear that the "
"returned value is actually borrowing something. Therefore, starting with "
"Rust 2018, it is deprecated to leave off the lifetime parameters for non-"
"reference-types (types other than `&` and `&mut`). Instead, where you "
"previously wrote `-> StrWrap`, you should now write `-> StrWrap<'_>`, making "
"clear that borrowing is occurring."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:66
msgid ""
"What exactly does `'_` mean? It depends on the context! In output contexts, "
"as in the return type of `make_wrapper`, it refers to a single lifetime for  "
"all \"output\" locations. In input contexts, a fresh lifetime is generated "
"for each \"input location\". More concretely, to understand input contexts, "
"consider the following example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:80
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:96
msgid "// some methods...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:84
msgid "We can rewrite this as:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:100
msgid ""
"This is the same, because for each `'_`, a fresh lifetime is generated. "
"Finally, the relationship `'a: 'b` which the struct requires must be upheld."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:103
msgid ""
"For more details, see the [tracking issue on In-band lifetime bindings]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/44524)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/index.md:1
msgid "Platform and target support"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/index.md:5
msgid ""
"In this chapter of the guide, we discuss a few improvements to platform and "
"target support. A notable addition to it was [that the `libcore` library now "
"works on stable Rust](rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-"
"level-rust.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:1
msgid "cdylib crates for C interoperability"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.10](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.10-brightgreen.svg) for `rustc`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:5
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.11](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.11-brightgreen.svg) for `cargo`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:7
msgid ""
"If you're producing a library that you intend to be used from C (or another "
"language through a C FFI), there's no need for Rust to include Rust-specific "
"stuff in the final object code. For libraries like that, you'll want to use "
"the `cdylib` crate type in your `Cargo.toml`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:12
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[lib]\n"
"crate-type = [\"cdylib\"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/cdylib-crates-for-c-interoperability.md:17
msgid ""
"This will produce a smaller binary, with no Rust-specific information inside "
"of it."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:1
msgid "Global allocators"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.28](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.28-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:5
msgid ""
"Allocators are the way that programs in Rust obtain memory from the system "
"at runtime. Previously, Rust did not allow changing the way memory is "
"obtained, which prevented some use cases. On some platforms, this meant "
"using jemalloc, on others, the system allocator, but there was no way for "
"users to control this key component. With 1.28.0, the `#[global_allocator]` "
"attribute is now stable, which allows Rust programs to set their allocator "
"to the system allocator, as well as define new allocators by implementing "
"the `GlobalAlloc` trait."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:14
msgid ""
"The default allocator for Rust programs on some platforms is jemalloc. The "
"standard library now provides a handle to the system allocator, which can be "
"used to switch to the system allocator when desired, by declaring a static "
"and marking it with the `#[global_allocator]` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:27
msgid "// This will allocate memory using the system allocator.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:32
msgid ""
"However, sometimes you want to define a custom allocator for a given "
"application domain. This is also relatively easy to do by implementing the "
"`GlobalAlloc` trait. You can read more about how to do this in [the "
"documentation](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/alloc/trait.GlobalAlloc.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-level-rust.md:1
msgid "libcore for low-level Rust"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-level-rust.md:5
msgid ""
"Rust’s standard library is two-tiered: there’s a small core library, "
"`libcore`, and the full standard library, `libstd`, that builds on top of "
"it. `libcore` is completely platform agnostic, and requires only a handful "
"of external symbols to be defined. Rust’s `libstd` builds on top of "
"`libcore`, adding support for things like memory allocation and I/O. "
"Applications using Rust in the embedded space, as well as those writing "
"operating systems, often eschew `libstd`, using only `libcore`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-level-rust.md:13
msgid ""
"As an additional note, while building _libraries_ with `libcore` is "
"supported today, building full applications is not yet stable."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-level-rust.md:16
msgid "To use `libcore`, add this flag to your crate root:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-level-rust.md:22
msgid ""
"This will remove the standard library, and bring the `core` crate into your "
"namespace for use:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-level-rust.md:31
msgid ""
"You can find `libcore`'s documentation [here](https://doc.rust-lang.org/"
"core/)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/msvc-toolchain-support.md:1
msgid "MSVC toolchain support"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/msvc-toolchain-support.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.2](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.2-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/msvc-toolchain-support.md:5
msgid ""
"At the release of Rust 1.0, we only supported the GNU toolchain on Windows. "
"With the release of Rust 1.2, we introduced initial support for the MSVC "
"toolchain. After that, as support matured, we eventually made it the default "
"choice for Windows users."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/msvc-toolchain-support.md:9
msgid ""
"The difference between the two matters for interacting with C. If you're "
"using a library built with one toolchain or another, you need to match that "
"with the appropriate Rust toolchain. If you're not sure, go with MSVC; it's "
"the default for good reason."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/msvc-toolchain-support.md:13
msgid ""
"To use this feature, simply use Rust on Windows, and the installer will "
"default to it. If you'd prefer to switch to the GNU toolchain, you can "
"install it with Rustup:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:1
msgid "MUSL support for fully static binaries"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:5
msgid ""
"By default, Rust will statically link all Rust code. However, if you use the "
"standard library, it will dynamically link to the system's `libc` "
"implementation."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:9
msgid ""
"If you'd like a 100% static binary, the [`MUSL libc`](https://www.musl-libc."
"org/) can be used on Linux."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:12
msgid "Installing MUSL support"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:14
msgid ""
"To add support for MUSL, you need to choose the correct target. [The forge "
"has a full list of targets](https://forge.rust-lang.org/platform-support."
"html) supported, with a number of ones using `musl`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:19
msgid ""
"If you're not sure what you want, it's probably `x86_64-unknown-linux-musl`, "
"for 64-bit Linux. We'll be using this target in this guide, but the "
"instructions remain the same for other targets, just change the name "
"wherever we mention the target."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:24
msgid "To get support for this target, you use `rustup`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:30
msgid ""
"This will install support for the default toolchain; to install for other "
"toolchains, add the `--toolchain` flag. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:37
msgid "Building with MUSL"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:39
msgid "To use this new target, pass the `--target` flag to Cargo:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/musl-support-for-fully-static-binaries.md:45
msgid "The binary produced will now be built with MUSL!"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:1
msgid "WebAssembly support"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.14](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.14-brightgreen.svg) for `emscripten`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:5
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: nightly](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-nightly-red.svg) for `wasm32-unknown-unknown`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:7
msgid ""
"Rust has gained support for [WebAssembly](https://webassembly.org/), meaning "
"that you can run Rust code in your browser, client-side."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:10
msgid ""
"In Rust 1.14, we gained support through [emscripten](http://kripken.github."
"io/emscripten-site/index.html). With it installed, you can write Rust code "
"and have it produce [asm.js](http://asmjs.org/) (the precusor to wasm) and/"
"or WebAssembly."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:15
msgid "Here's an example of using this support:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:17
msgid ""
"```console\n"
"$ rustup target add wasm32-unknown-emscripten\n"
"$ echo 'fn main() { println!(\"Hello, Emscripten!\"); }' > hello.rs\n"
"$ rustc --target=wasm32-unknown-emscripten hello.rs\n"
"$ node hello.js\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:24
msgid ""
"However, in the meantime, Rust has also grown its own support, independent "
"from Emscripten. This is known as \"the unknown target\", because instead of "
"`wasm32-unknown-emscripten`, it's `wasm32-unknown-unknown`. This will be the "
"preferred target to use once it's ready, but for now, it's really only well-"
"supported in nightly."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/index.md:1
msgid "`rustdoc`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/index.md:5
msgid ""
"In this chapter of the guide, we discuss a few improvements to `rustdoc`. A "
"notable addition to it was [that documentation tests can now compile-fail]"
"(rust-2018/rustdoc/documentation-tests-can-now-compile-fail.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/documentation-tests-can-now-compile-fail.md:1
msgid "Documentation tests can now compile-fail"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/documentation-tests-can-now-compile-fail.md:5
msgid "You can now create `compile-fail` tests in Rustdoc, like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/documentation-tests-can-now-compile-fail.md:7
msgid ""
"````\n"
"/// ```compile_fail\n"
"/// let x = 5;\n"
"/// x += 2; // shouldn't compile!\n"
"/// ```\n"
"# fn foo() {}\n"
"````"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/documentation-tests-can-now-compile-fail.md:15
msgid ""
"Please note that these kinds of tests can be more fragile than others, as "
"additions to Rust may cause code to compile when it previously would not. "
"Consider the first release with `?`, for example: code using `?` would fail "
"to compile on Rust 1.21, but compile successfully on Rust 1.22, causing your "
"test suite to start failing."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/rustdoc-uses-commonmark.md:1
msgid "Rustdoc uses CommonMark"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/rustdoc-uses-commonmark.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.25](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.25-brightgreen.svg) for support by default"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/rustdoc-uses-commonmark.md:5
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.23](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.23-red.svg) for support via a flag"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/rustdoc-uses-commonmark.md:7
msgid ""
"Rustdoc lets you write documentation comments in Markdown. At Rust 1.0, we "
"were using the `hoedown` markdown implementation, written in C. Markdown is "
"more of a family of implementations of an idea, and so `hoedown` had its own "
"dialect, like many parsers. The [CommonMark project](https://commonmark."
"org/) has attempted to define a more strict version of Markdown, and so now, "
"Rustdoc uses it by default."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/rustdoc-uses-commonmark.md:14
msgid ""
"As of Rust 1.23, we still defaulted to `hoedown`, but you could enable "
"Commonmark via a flag, `--enable-commonmark`. Today, we only support "
"CommonMark."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:1
msgid "Rustup for managing Rust versions"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: various](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-various-brightgreen.svg) (this tool has its own "
"versioning scheme and works with all Rust versions)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:5
msgid ""
"The [Rustup](https://rustup.rs/) tool has become _the_ recommended way to "
"install Rust, and is advertised on our website. Its powers go further than "
"that though, allowing you to manage various versions, components, and "
"platforms."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:10
msgid "For installing Rust"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:12
msgid ""
"To install Rust through Rustup, you can go to <https://www.rust-lang.org/"
"install.html>, which will let you know how to do so on your platform. This "
"will install both `rustup` itself and the `stable` version of `rustc` and "
"`cargo`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:17
msgid "To install a specific Rust version, you can use `rustup install`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:23
msgid "This works for a specific nightly, as well:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:29
msgid "As well as any of our release channels:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:37
msgid "For updating your installation"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:39
msgid "To update all of the various channels you may have installed:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:45
msgid ""
"This will look at everything you've installed, and if there are new "
"releases, will update anything that has one."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:48
msgid "Managing versions"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:50
msgid "To set the default toolchain to something other than `stable`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:56
msgid "To use a toolchain other than the default, use `rustup run`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:62
msgid "There's also an alias for this that's a little shorter:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:68
msgid ""
"If you'd like to have a different default per-directory, that's easy too! If "
"you run this inside of a project:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:75
msgid ""
"Then when you're in that directory, any invocations of `rustc` or `cargo` "
"will use that toolchain. To share this with others, you can create a `rust-"
"toolchain` file with the contents of a toolchain, and check it into source "
"control. Now, when someone clones your project, they'll get the right "
"version without needing to `override set` themselves."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:81
msgid "Installing other targets"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:83
msgid ""
"Rust supports cross-compiling to other targets, and Rustup can help you "
"manage them. For example, to use MUSL:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:90
msgid "And then you can"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:96
msgid "To see the full list of targets you can install:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:102
msgid "Installing components"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:104
msgid ""
"Components are used to install certain kinds of tools. While `cargo-install` "
"has you covered for most tools, some tools need deep integration into the "
"compiler. Rustup knows exactly what version of the compiler you're using, "
"and so it's got just the information that these tools need."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:109
msgid ""
"Components are per-toolchain, so if you want them to be available to more "
"than one toolchain, you'll need to install them multiple times. In the "
"following examples, add a `--toolchain` flag, set to the toolchain you want "
"to install for, `nightly` for example. Without this flag, it will install "
"the component for the default toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:115
msgid "To see the full list of components you can install:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:121
msgid ""
"Next, let's talk about some popular components and when you might want to "
