#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:42
msgid ""
"Traits have an extra ability with associated constants that gives them some "
"extra power. With a trait, you can use an associated constant in the same "
"way you’d use an associated type: by declaring it, but not giving it a "
"value. The implementor of the trait then declares its value upon "
"implementation:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:63
msgid ""
"Before this feature, if you wanted to make a trait that represented floating "
"point numbers, you’d have to write this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:74
msgid ""
"This is slightly unwieldy, but more importantly, because they’re functions, "
"they cannot be used in constant expressions, even though they only return a "
"constant. Because of this, a design for `Float` would also have to include "
"constants as well:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:95
msgid ""
"Associated constants let you do this in a much cleaner way. This trait "
"definition:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:106
msgid "Leads to this implementation:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:117
msgid "much cleaner, and more versatile."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/dyn-trait-for-trait-objects.md:1
msgid "`dyn Trait` for trait objects"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/dyn-trait-for-trait-objects.md:5
msgid ""
"The `dyn Trait` feature is the new syntax for using trait objects. In short:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/dyn-trait-for-trait-objects.md:7
msgid "`Box<Trait>` becomes `Box<dyn Trait>`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/dyn-trait-for-trait-objects.md:8
msgid "`&Trait` and `&mut Trait` become `&dyn Trait` and `&mut dyn Trait`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/dyn-trait-for-trait-objects.md:10
msgid "And so on. In code:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/dyn-trait-for-trait-objects.md:28
msgid "That's it!"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/dyn-trait-for-trait-objects.md:32
msgid ""
"Using just the trait name for trait objects turned out to be a bad decision. "
"The current syntax is often ambiguous and confusing, even to veterans, and "
"favors a feature that is not more frequently used than its alternatives, is "
"sometimes slower, and often cannot be used at all when its alternatives can."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/dyn-trait-for-trait-objects.md:37
msgid ""
"Furthermore, with `impl Trait` arriving, \"`impl Trait` vs `dyn Trait`\" is "
"much more symmetric, and therefore a bit nicer, than \"`impl Trait` vs "
"`Trait`\". `impl Trait` is explained [here](rust-2018/trait-system/impl-"
"trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.html)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/dyn-trait-for-trait-objects.md:41
msgid ""
"In the new edition, you should therefore prefer `dyn Trait` to just `Trait` "
"where you need a trait object."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:1
msgid "`impl Trait` for returning complex types with ease"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:5
msgid ""
"`impl Trait` is the new way to specify unnamed but concrete types that "
"implement a specific trait. There are two places you can put it: argument "
"position, and return position."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:11
msgid "// argument position\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:15
msgid "// return position\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:21
msgid "Argument Position"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:23
msgid ""
"In argument position, this feature is quite simple. These two forms are "
"almost the same:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:36
msgid ""
"That is, it's a slightly shorter syntax for a generic type parameter. It "
"means, \"`arg` is an argument that takes any type that implements the "
"`Trait` trait.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:40
msgid ""
"However, there's also an important technical difference between `T: Trait` "
"and `impl Trait` here. When you write the former, you can specify the type "
"of `T` at the call site with turbo-fish syntax as with `foo::<usize>(1)`. In "
"the case of `impl Trait`, if it is used anywhere in the function definition, "
"then you can't use turbo-fish at all. Therefore, you should be mindful that "
"changing both from and to `impl Trait` can constitute a breaking change for "
"the users of your code."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:48
msgid "Return Position"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:50
msgid ""
"In return position, this feature is more interesting. It means \"I am "
"returning some type that implements the `Trait` trait, but I'm not going to "
"tell you exactly what the type is.\" Before `impl Trait`, you could do this "
"with trait objects:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:65
msgid ""
"However, this has some overhead: the `Box<T>` means that there's a heap "
"allocation here, and this will use dynamic dispatch. See the `dyn Trait` "
"section for an explanation of this syntax. But we only ever return one "
"possible thing here, the `Box<i32>`. This means that we're paying for "
"dynamic dispatch, even though we don't use it!"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:71
msgid "With `impl Trait`, the code above could be written like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:83
msgid ""
"Here, we have no `Box<T>`, no trait object, and no dynamic dispatch. But we "
"still can obscure the `i32` return type."
