#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:113
msgid "We can now return closures by value, just like any other type!"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:117
msgid ""
"The above is all you need to know to get going with `impl Trait`, but for "
"some more nitty-gritty details: type parameters and `impl Trait` work "
"slightly differently when they're in argument position versus return "
"position. Consider this function:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:126
msgid ""
"When you call it, you set the type, `T`. \"you\" being the caller here. This "
"signature says \"I accept any type that implements Trait.\" (\"any type\" == "
"universal in the jargon)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:130
msgid "This version:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:136
msgid ""
"is similar, but also different. You, the caller, provide the type you want, "
"`T`, and then the function returns it. You can see this in Rust today with "
"things like parse or collect:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:141
#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:142
msgid "\"5\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:145
msgid "Here, `.parse` has this signature:"
