#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:152
msgid ""
"Same general idea, though with a result type and `FromStr` has an associated "
"type... anyway, you can see how `F` is in the return position here. So you "
"have the ability to choose."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:156
msgid ""
"With `impl Trait`, you're saying \"hey, some type exists that implements "
"this trait, but I'm not gonna tell you what it is.\". So now, the caller "
"can't choose, and the function itself gets to choose. If we tried to define "
"parse with `Result<impl F,...` as the return type, it wouldn't work."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:161
msgid "Using `impl Trait` in more places"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:163
msgid ""
"As previously mentioned, as a start, you will only be able to use `impl "
"Trait` as the argument or return type of a free or inherent function. "
"However, `impl Trait` can't be used inside implementations of traits, nor "
"can it be used as the type of a let binding or inside a type alias. Some of "
"these restrictions will eventually be lifted. For more information, see the "
"[tracking issue on `impl Trait`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"issues/34511)."
msgstr ""

