#: src/editions/index.md:1
msgid "What are Editions?"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:3
msgid ""
"Rust ships releases on a six-week cycle. This means that users get a "
"constant stream of new features. This is much faster than updates for other "
"languages, but this also means that each update is smaller.  After a while, "
"all of those tiny changes add up. But, from release to release, it can be "
"hard to look back and say _\"Wow, between Rust 1.10 and Rust 1.20, Rust has "
"changed a lot!\"_"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:9
msgid ""
"Every two or three years, we'll be producing a new _edition_ of Rust. Each "
"edition brings together the features that have landed into a clear package, "
"with fully updated documentation and tooling. New editions ship through the "
"usual release process."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:14
msgid "This serves different purposes for different people:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:16
msgid ""
"For active Rust users, it brings together incremental changes into an easy-"
"to-understand package."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:19
msgid ""
"For non-users, it signals that some major advancements have landed, which "
"might make Rust worth another look."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:22
msgid ""
"For those developing Rust itself, it provides a rallying point for the "
"project as a whole."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:25
msgid "Compatibility"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:27
msgid ""
"When a new edition becomes available in the compiler, crates must explicitly "
"opt in to it to take full advantage. This opt in enables editions to contain "
"incompatible changes, like adding a new keyword that might conflict with "
"identifiers in code, or turning warnings into errors. A Rust compiler will "
"support all editions that existed prior to the compiler's release, and can "
"link crates of any supported editions together. Edition changes only affect "
"the way the compiler initially parses the code. Therefore, if you're using "
"Rust 2015, and one of your dependencies uses Rust 2018, it all works just "
"fine. The opposite situation works as well."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:38
msgid ""
"Just to be clear: most features will be available on all editions. People "
"using any edition of Rust will continue to see improvements as new stable "
"releases are made.  In some cases however, mainly when new keywords are "
"added, but sometimes for other reasons, there may be new features that are "
"only available in later editions.  You only need to upgrade if you want to "
"take advantage of such features."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:45
msgid "Trying out the 2018 edition"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:47
msgid ""
"At the time of writing, there are two editions: 2015 and 2018. 2015 is "
"today's Rust; Rust 2018 is currently in beta, and will land in stable in "
"Rust 1.31, on December 6, 2018."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:50
msgid "To give the 2018 edition a try, install the beta toolchain:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:56
msgid "If you want the really bleeding edge, you can try nightly:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/index.md:62
msgid ""
"When you see commands like `cargo fix` elsewhere in this guide, you may need "
"to preface them with the toolchain:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/creating-a-new-project.md:3
msgid ""
"When you create a new project with Cargo, it will automatically add "
"configuration for the latest edition:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/creating-a-new-project.md:6
msgid ""
"```console\n"
"> cargo +nightly new foo\n"
"     Created binary (application) `foo` project\n"
"> cat .\\foo\\Cargo.toml\n"
"[package]\n"
"name = \"foo\"\n"
"version = \"0.1.0\"\n"
"authors = [\"your name <you@example.com>\"]\n"
"edition = \"2018\"\n"
"\n"
"[dependencies]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/creating-a-new-project.md:19
msgid ""
"That `edition = \"2018\"` setting will configure your package to use Rust "
"2018. No more configuration needed!"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/creating-a-new-project.md:22
msgid ""
"If you'd prefer to use an older edition, you can change the value in that "
"key, for example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/creating-a-new-project.md:25
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[package]\n"
"name = \"foo\"\n"
"version = \"0.1.0\"\n"
"authors = [\"your name <you@example.com>\"]\n"
"edition = \"2015\"\n"
"\n"
"[dependencies]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/creating-a-new-project.md:35
msgid "This will build your package in Rust 2015."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:3
msgid ""
"New editions might change the way you write Rust – they add new syntax, "
"language, and library features, and also remove features. For example, "
"`try`, `async`, and `await` are keywords in Rust 2018, but not Rust 2015. If "
"you have a project that's using Rust 2015, and you'd like to use Rust 2018 "
"for it instead, there's a few steps that you need to take."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:9
msgid ""
"It's our intention that the migration to new editions is as smooth an "
"experience as possible. If it's difficult for you to upgrade to Rust 2018, "
"we consider that a bug. If you run into problems with this process, please "
"[file a bug](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/new). Thank you!"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:14
msgid ""
"Here's an example. Imagine we have a crate that has this code in `src/lib."
"rs`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:23
msgid ""
"This code uses an anonymous parameter, that `Box<Foo>`. This is [not "
"supported in Rust 2018](rust-2018/trait-system/no-anon-params.html), and so "
"this would fail to compile. Let's get this code up to date!"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:27
msgid "Updating your code to be compatible with the new edition"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:29
msgid ""
"Your code may or may not use features that are incompatible with the new "
"edition. In order to help transition to Rust 2018, we've included a new "
"subcommand with Cargo. To start, let's run it:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:37
msgid ""
"This will check your code, and automatically fix any issues that it can. "
"Let's look at `src/lib.rs` again:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:46
msgid ""
"It's re-written our code to introduce a parameter name for that trait "
"object. In this case, since it had no name, `cargo fix` will replace it with "
"`_`, which is conventional for unusued variables."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:50
msgid ""
"`cargo fix` is still pretty new, and so it can't always fix your code "
"automatically. If `cargo fix` can't fix something, it will print the warning "
"that it cannot fix to the console. If you see one of these warnings, you'll "
"have to update your code manually. See the corresponding section of this "
"guide for help, and if you have problems, please seek help at the [user's "
"forums](https://users.rust-lang.org/)."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:56
msgid "Keep running `cargo fix --edition` until you have no more warnings."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:58
msgid "Congrats! Your code is now valid in both Rust 2015 and Rust 2018!"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:60
msgid "Enabling the new edition to use new features"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:62
msgid ""
"In order to use some new features, you must explicitly opt in to the new "
"edition. Once you're ready to commit, change your `Cargo.toml` to add the "
"new `edition` key/value pair. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:66
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[package]\n"
"name = \"foo\"\n"
"version = \"0.1.0\"\n"
"authors = [\"Your Name <you@example.com>\"]\n"
"edition = \"2018\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:74
msgid ""
"If there's no `edition` key, Cargo will default to Rust 2015. But in this "
"case, we've chosen `2018`, and so our code is compiling with Rust 2018!"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:77
msgid "Writing idiomatic code in a new edition"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:79
msgid ""
"Editions are not only about new features and removing old ones. In any "
"programming language, idioms change over time, and Rust is no exception. "
"While old code will continue to compile, it might be written with different "
"idioms today."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:83
msgid "Our sample code contains an outdated idiom. Here it is again:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:91
msgid ""
"In Rust 2018, it's considered idiomatic to use the [`dyn` keyword](rust-2018/"
"trait-system/dyn-trait-for-trait-objects.html) for trait objects."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:95
msgid ""
"Eventually, we want `cargo fix` to fix all these idioms automatically in the "
"same manner we did for upgrading to the 2018 edition. **Currently, though, "
"the _\"idiom lints\"_ are not ready for widespread automatic fixing.** The "
"compiler isn't making `cargo fix`\\-compatible suggestions in many cases "
"right now, and it is making incorrect suggestions in others. Enabling the "
"idiom lints, even with `cargo fix`, is likely to leave your crate either "
"broken or with many warnings still remaining."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:103
msgid ""
"We have plans to make these idiom migrations a seamless part of the Rust "
"2018 experience, but we're not there yet. As a result the following "
"instructions are recommended only for the intrepid who are willing to work "
"through a few compiler/Cargo bugs!"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:108
msgid ""
"With that out of the way, we can instruct Cargo to fix our code snippet with:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:114
msgid "Afterwards, `src/lib.rs` looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:122
msgid "We're now more idiomatic, and we didn't have to fix our code manually!"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:124
msgid ""
"Note that `cargo fix` may still not be able to automatically update our "
"code. If `cargo fix` can't fix something, it will print a warning to the "
"console, and you'll have to fix it manually."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:128
msgid ""
"As mentioned before, there are known bugs around the idiom lints which means "
"they're not all ready for prime time yet. You may get a scary-looking "
"warning to report a bug to Cargo, which happens whenever a fix proposed by "
"`rustc` actually caused code to stop compiling by accident. If you'd like "
"`cargo fix` to make as much progress as possible, even if it causes code to "
"stop compiling, you can execute:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:139
msgid ""
"This will instruct `cargo fix` to apply automatic suggestions regardless of "
"whether they work or not. Like usual, you'll see the compilation result "
"after all fixes are applied. If you notice anything wrong or unusual, please "
"feel free to report an issue to Cargo and we'll help prioritize and fix it."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions/transitioning-an-existing-project-to-a-new-edition.md:144
msgid "Enjoy the new edition!"
msgstr ""
